# HPU Brand Voice Skill

Use this skill when writing copy in High Point University's voice. The skill covers blog posts, press releases, admissions and parent-recruitment pages, tuition and value pitches, student life materials, internal staff comms, presidential emails, athletics promo, religious life copy, philanthropy and development letters, video scripts, and long-form commemorative writing.

## Voice in one line

Aspirational, abundant, and proud. HPU writes like a confident host walking you around a place they genuinely believe is special, naming everything by its proper name and citing every number they have.

## Core identity

The reader is usually "you," a prospective student or family member. Every sentence sells the experience. Excellence is treated as the baseline, not the achievement. Modesty is not a feature of this voice.

When in doubt: name the building, name the person, name the program, cite the stat.

## The four foundational pillars

HPU organizes its identity around four pillars. The centennial magazine defines each as a noun. When writing big-frame HPU content, anchor sections or arguments to one of these.

1. **Academic Innovation**. Curriculum, learning environments, and accomplished professors that change the lives of students. A commitment to lifelong learning and excellence inside and outside the classroom.
2. **Premier Life Skills**. The skill set graduates use to navigate ambiguity, adapt in shifting conditions, solve complex problems, communicate well, and represent their organization at the highest level. HPU's branded answer to what employers say grads lack.
3. **Experiential Learning**. Hands-on, real-world application. 25% of classes have an experiential component. Access to Innovators, externships, internships, learning labs, and on-site work with industry leaders.
4. **Values**. God, family, and country. Service, generosity, gratitude, civility, respect, patriotism, faith, and an appreciation for the entrepreneurial spirit. Lived through traditions like the Honor Code signing and the Veterans Day Celebration.

## The 12 voice registers

HPU has one voice across 12 registers. Match the register to the content type before writing.

1. **Blog/feature**. Peppy, exclamation-friendly, second-person, CTA-heavy. Listicles, value-prop pieces, profiles, photo-op showcases.
2. **Press release**. Third-person, dateline format, multiple sourced quotes, sponsor close. Events, awards, guest speaker visits, announcements.
3. **Admissions/recruitment (prospective student)**. Second-person, command verbs (Apply, Tour, Discover), counselor-as-advocate, conversational asides. Landing pages, application steps, deadline copy.
4. **Parent recruitment**. Refers to "your student" or "your child" rather than addressing the prospective student directly. Bullet differentiators, parent testimonials, Princeton Review framing. The For Parents page sits here.
5. **Tuition/value**. Investment framing, peer comparisons, complimentary-services lists. Cost and ROI pages.
6. **Welcome Week / Student Life**. Welcome Home greeting, hashtag-driven, mandatory event markers, casual visit verbs. Orientation, move-in, residence life.
7. **President Qubein first-person**. Salutation is "Dear HPU Family" or named individual. Capitalized YOUR for emphasis. Warm closers like "we love you and we miss you." Signed emails and letters.
8. **Internal/operational**. Caring Campus Tip format, "Did You Know" callouts, hospitality reminders. Campus Concierge newsletters, faculty-staff comms.
9. **Athletics game-day**. "17 Teams. 1 Family." anchors the tone. Fight song framing, "Go Panthers!" closer. Hype Night, game promos, pep rallies.
10. **Religious Life**. Warmer tone, less promotional. Uses "join us" and "all are welcome." Chapel, Hillel, Catholic Mass copy.
11. **Development / philanthropy**. Salutation "Dear High Point University Families." Gratitude-led. Names giving programs. Signed by VP for Development. Family Engagement letters, annual fund appeals.
12. **Long-form magazine / commemorative**. Definitional sidebars (defining pillars as nouns), decade-by-decade timelines, pull quotes from luminaries, family legacy profiles, statistical comparison tables. The Centennial Magazine is the model.

A useful 13th frame: **The College Tour / broadcast scripts**, where students and a host address camera, exchange "back to you, Alex," and treat the video as a tour.

## Mission statement and signature taglines

### The full mission statement
"At High Point University, every student receives an extraordinary education in an inspiring environment with caring people.®"

This is the most-quoted line in HPU copy. Use the full version when introducing the university to outsiders.

### Other signature phrases (not trademarked but lexicon)

Welcome Home (move-in / orientation greeting). Our City. Our University. (local partnership program). 17 Teams. 1 Family. (athletics). We Heart HPU (local signage). Caring Campus (internal culture). Healthy obsession (admissions self-description). 100 Extraordinary Years (centennial framing). Faithful courage (Qubein's term for past leaders). Different with relevance (Qubein's positioning). Heroes, models and mentors. Success and significance. Lifelong return on investment. 500-acre classroom. Hub of [activity]. Real-world. Hands-on. Learning labs. State-of-the-art. Cutting-edge. World-class.

### Centennial-specific framing

The university celebrated its centennial in the 2024-25 academic year (founded September 1924). When writing in 2024-2025, reference "100 Extraordinary Years" or "100-year history." When writing about the 2005-to-present transformation as a distinct era, use "transformational growth plan" or "the transformation since 2005" as a proper-noun-style reference, not generic praise.

### Hashtags in active use

#HPUMoveIn. #HPUFamily. #HPU[YearClass] (e.g., #HPU2029). #TransformationTuesday. #FlashbackFriday. Plus accounts: @hpugreeks, @HPUCAT, @HPUREC, @sga_highpoint, @highpointpanthers.

