## Buildings and campus geography

### Academic and administrative
Roberts Hall (the original symbol; 1923; named for John Calvin Roberts; cost $120,000). Cottrell Hall (43,000 sq ft, 2015; houses Flanagan Center for Student Success, Mestdagh Commons 2nd floor, Graves Collaboratorium 2nd floor, Kushner International Marketplace, International Student Concourse with airplane fuselage, Cottrell Starbucks, Dwyer Career & Professional Development). Slane Student Center. Congdon Hall (220,000 sq ft, $120M, 2017). Couch Hall. Norton Hall. Plato S. Wilson Hall. Phillips Hall (2005). Wanek School of Natural Sciences. Webb Hall (Optometry). Stout School of Education. Wrenn undergraduate admissions building. Webb Conference Center. Caine Conservatory. McInnis Hall (Empty Space Theatre / Black Box). Hayworth Fine Arts Center (2002, named for Charles E. Hayworth Jr. and Pauline; Pauline Theatre inside; $13M; home of Theater and Dance). Hayworth Memorial Chapel. Smith Library (1984; 50,000 sq ft; 140,000 books; 10,000 films; Jack Lucas's Medal of Honor on display). Martha Luck Comer Learning Commons (in R.G. Wanek Center).

### Innovation Corridor and STEM
The $500 million Innovation Corridor is a half-mile stretch of campus dedicated to STEM. Inside it: the MakerSpace (24/7 access with laser cutters, PCB mills, computer-controlled routers, vacuum formers, soldering gear); CELF (Cybersecurity Learning Facility, with its own internet connection); Haptic Simulation Lab at the dental school (10 SIMtoCARE dental simulation units); Human Biomechanics and Physiology Lab (zero-gravity treadmill, high-speed 3D motion-analysis cameras, bone density scanner, environmental chamber); Virtual Reality and Clinical Gait Analysis Lab; cadaver lab; human anatomy lab.

### Communication School facilities
Renovated TV studio designed to Hollywood standards (24-foot high-resolution video wall, 4K multicamera broadcast system, DMX-controlled lighting, customized news stage). Podcast Recording Studio. Screening Room. 40+ cameras for film majors. Social media simulator (Hootsuite Certification). Ascension 336 (student-run communications agency). Beacon Lab (research using eye tracking, galvanic skin response, heart rate monitoring). PRSSA chapter (Public Relations Student Society of America).

### Business school facilities
Trading room with live stock ticker and trading software. Executive boardrooms across campus. Criminal justice mock courtroom. Esports arena and game design lab.

### Residence halls (Tier 1 through Tier 5)
- Tier 1: Belk, Finch, McEwen, Millis, North, Wesley, Yadkin (doubles)
- Tier 2: Finch and McEwen singles; University Center II and R.G. Wanek Center doubles; Blessing 3-4 BR apartments
- Tier 3: Panther Commons 4-person suites (doubles); 200,000 sq ft, 5 stories, 400 students
- Tier 4: Blessing 2-BR suites
- Tier 5: R.G. Wanek and University Center II singles

Other residential: Centennial Square I and II (with Boles Commons and Samuel Commons); Greek Village (2011); Aldridge Village; North College Station; U-Ville Apartments; Parkway Commons; Point Place Apartments (806, 812, 818); University Landing / McCain Place Townhomes; Caffey, Wilson, York; College Village (houses Bergman Family Hillel House at Suite 1197).

Honors students live in Finch Honors Living Residence Hall. 98% of freshmen are in Tier 1 or Tier 2. HPU students live on campus until senior status. 95% of the student body lives on campus.

### Arena, athletics, and outdoor
Nido and Mariana Qubein Arena and Conference Center ($170 million, 350,000 sq ft, opened September 2021; arena holds 5,000 fans; conference center 1,500 attendees; Jana and Ken Kahn Hotel houses 60 guests). Millis Athletic and Convocation Center. Vert Stadium (soccer; Witcher Athletic Center at Vert Stadium, 36,000 sq ft, 2014, $20M endowment from Doug Witcher). Coy O. Williard Baseball Stadium / Erath Baseball Field. Steele Sports Center. Ike Belk Track. HPU Estate and Ropes Course. Cottrell Amphitheater. Mariana H. Qubein Arboretum and Botanical Gardens (31 gardens, 3,700 plants, 700+ tree varieties; 48 redbuds, 65 dogwoods, 40 flowering apricots, 135 magnolias). Cottrell Japanese Garden (designed by Sadafumi Uchiyama, gift from David and Christy Cottrell). Kester International Promenade (52+ nations' flags). David R. Hayworth Park (waterfall, Dream Big chairs). Murdock Patriots Plaza. Roberts Reflecting Pool on the Elizabeth Miller Strickland Scholarship Plaza. Innovation Corridor / Mahler Promenade. Celebration Plaza. Extraordinary Way (the street between Blessing Way and Panther Drive).

