## Founding history and key dates

- **1894:** McCulloch challenges NC Methodist Conference: "It takes men of faith to bring things to pass."
- **1901:** John Calvin Roberts pledges $10,000.
- **June 29, 1922:** Cornerstone laid for Roberts Hall (named for John Calvin Roberts).
- **July 1924:** Dr. Robert Macon Andrews selected as first president.
- **September 14, 1924:** Classes begin. 9 faculty, 122 students, 3 buildings, 60 acres, 10 majors.
- **1933:** During Great Depression, students from rural NC pay tuition with farm goods (vegetables, corn, wheat, chickens, hog meat, beef, cotton, peanuts).
- **June 15, 1935:** Order of the Lighted Lamp founded (faculty-student honor society).
- **1962:** Thad Lowrey graduates (start of three-generation Lowrey family legacy at HPU).
- **April 1985:** Dr. Jacob Martinson becomes 6th president.
- **1984:** Smith Library opens. 50,000 sq ft. Replaces Wrenn Library. Cost: $3M.
- **1990:** NCDOT authorizes relocation of Montlieu Avenue to make room for Hayworth Fine Arts Center.
- **October 9, 1991:** Board of Trustees votes; High Point College becomes High Point University.
- **1993:** First graduate program begins (master's in management and international management).
- **January 2005:** Nido Qubein becomes 7th president; alumnus (HPC '70, human relations).
- **February 2005:** Qubein raises $20 million in 29 days; presents $60 million growth plan.
- **2005:** Phillips School of Business opens; campus is 91 acres, 3 schools, 1,673 students, 108 faculty.
- **2007:** Blessing Hall.
- **2008:** Wilson Commerce Hall.
- **2009:** Nido R. Qubein School of Communication; R.G. Wanek Center.
- **2011:** Greek Village.
- **2012:** Stout School of Education.
- **2014:** Witcher Athletic Center (36,000 sq ft).
- **2015:** Cottrell Hall (43,000 sq ft); first Athletics Hall of Fame class inducted.
- **March 2016:** Steve Wozniak first visit. Access to Innovators Program launches.
- **May 2016:** First doctoral graduates (14 EdDs).
- **September 2017:** Congdon Hall opens (220,000 sq ft, $120 million). Houses Congdon School of Health Sciences and Fred Wilson School of Pharmacy.
- **September 2021:** Nido and Mariana Qubein Arena and Conference Center + Jana and Ken Kahn Hotel open ($170 million, 350,000 sq ft).
- **March 2022:** Three families gift $100 million combined for new schools.
- **August 2024:** Record total enrollment 6,300+; largest entering class 1,650; opens Workman School of Dental Medicine, Kenneth F. Kahn School of Law, David S. Congdon School of Entrepreneurship.
- **2024-25:** Centennial year. "100 Extraordinary Years."

