## Register-specific sentence patterns

### Blog/feature register
- Second-person address ("You'll feel the roaring energy")
- Rhetorical questions as section openers
- "From X to Y" lists
- Pro-tip callouts (literal label)
- Active-verb headlines per list item
- Quote attribution: name, class year, current employer
- Sentence fragments for rhythm in feature profiles only

### Press release register
- Dateline: "HIGH POINT, N.C., [Month Day, Year] – High Point University® [news verb]..."
- Third-person throughout
- Quote attribution: "[Quote]," said [Name], [title]. Student quotes add hometown.
- Multiple sourced voices: President or First Lady, department lead, student, sponsor
- Photo captions embedded in copy
- Sponsor close
- No exclamation points
- Declarative headlines

### Admissions/recruitment (prospective student) register
- Hero phrase: "You Were Meant to be Extraordinary®"
- Command verbs as CTAs: Apply, Tour, Discover, Schedule a Visit, Begin Application, Request Information, Find Your Counselor
- Conversational asides allowed
- Counselor framed as advocate, not process
- Numbered application steps with full instructional sentences
- "Healthy obsession" signature phrase
- Capitalized YOU for emphasis

### Parent recruitment register
- Refers to "your student" or "your child" (not "you")
- Mission statement quoted directly
- Bullet differentiators in short sentences: "Different with relevance. Student-centered. Values-based. Pristine. Safe. Holistic learning environment."
- Parent testimonial quotes with full names and graduation year of their child
- Princeton Review rankings cited prominently
- Stats at top of page: Total Enrollment, Faculty Ratio, Employment, #1 Ranking
- Sections like "Differential Advantages," "Long-Term Success," "Merit-Based Scholarships," "Success Coaches"
- More "he or she" usage than other registers (HPU page does this; can be modernized to "they" for clearer writing)

### Tuition/value register
- Investment framing throughout
- Peer comparisons with dollar figures
- Complimentary services list (academic tutoring, parking, airport transport, Success Coach, Career Advisor, concierge, laundry, athletic events, LinkedIn photo)
- Parent testimonials with full names
- Math shown explicitly
- "Education with Value(s)" wordplay, sparingly

### Welcome Week / Student Life register
- Greeting: "Welcome Home"
- Hashtags throughout
- Time blocks formatted as "[Start]–[End]" with location and 1-3 sentence description
- Mandatory events explicitly labeled
- Casual visit verbs: "Drop in," "Swing by," "Come and join"
- Command openers: "Get ready to roll up your sleeves," "Kick off the semester"
- Energy closers: "Go Panthers!", "Come curious, leave inspired!", "This is a day you will never forget!"

### President Qubein first-person register
- Salutation: "Dear [Name]," or "Dear HPU Family,"
- Capitalized YOUR and YOU for emphasis
- Short paragraphs, often single sentences
- Direct claims of caring: "we love you and we miss you" / "there is nothing more important to me than YOUR success"
- Closer: "Sincerely, Nido Qubein, President"
- Names alumni or students when possible
- Uses "alma mater" and "HPU family" frequently

### Internal/operational register
- "Dear HPU Family," salutation for staff-wide
- Sections: Events/Opportunities, Did You Know, Caring Campus Tip, News, Student Highlight
- Caring Campus Tip is a one-sentence cultural reminder
- Hospitality-mindset framing for staff
- Closer: the full mission statement

### Athletics game-day register
- "17 Teams. 1 Family."
- "Go Panthers!" / "Go HPU!"
- "Get loud, get proud, get hyped"
- Matchup, venue, time as the lead
- Reference Prowler, cheer and dance teams, pep band, Celebration Plaza
- Patriotic threads work for big-game and ceremony copy

### Religious Life register
- "Join us" rather than "come"
- Lower exclamation rate
- "All are welcome" appears often
- Three values: Belonging, Becoming, Beholding
- Names the worship band, choir, gospel choir, minister
- Hillel copy uses Hebrew terms naturally
- Catholic Mass copy is more liturgical

### Development / philanthropy register
- Salutation: "Dear High Point University Families,"
- Tone: grateful, partnership-focused, warm but formal
- Names the giving fund (HPU Fund for Extraordinary Education)
- Cites scholarship support figure ($75 million annually)
- Three roles parents can play: advocacy through admissions, networking through Career Office, philanthropic giving
- Closer: "With Gratitude," then signed name, title, phone, email
- 501(c)(3) disclaimer at footer
- Specific named giving programs (President's Leadership Cabinet, Forever Families, Leave Your Mark)

### Long-form magazine / commemorative register
- Definitional sidebars (defining pillars as nouns)
- Decade-by-decade timeline format with year-banner anchors
- Pull quotes from luminaries (visually treated, often italicized)
- Family legacy profiles (Lowrey family, Lucenti and Conheeny families)
- Stats comparison tables (2005 vs 2024)
- "A Day in the Life" first-person student feature
- President's letter as opener ("Dear HPU Family,")
- Cross-references to QR codes and external content
- Quote from founder or early president can anchor a historical section

### Video / broadcast script register
- Conversational, address-the-camera style
- Host name (Alex) and student cast (Sophia Cina, Ja'Niyah Williams, Grant Hines, etc.)
- Handoff phrases: "Back to you, Alex." "Annie thanks Alex."
- Imperative travel cues: "A group of students and I travel to..."
- Mention places by full name (Dallas Mavericks headquarters, the Sport, Entertainment, Venues of Tomorrow Conference)
- Drop in the proof point: "HPU is nationally ranked in the top 10 for career services, and it's obvious why."

## Structural patterns by content type

**Blog listicle:** numbered items, bold headline per entry, 2-5 sentences, CTA in caps.

**Blog value-prop:** open with a Qubein-era anchor or framing quote. State X examples. Each has a named program, building or person, and a student/alumni quote with employer.

**Feature profile:** scene-set at a campus landmark. Backstory. Subhead break. HPU achievement. Named dialogue. Return to opening image as kicker.

**Photo-op showcase:** each landmark gets dimensions, exact location, and a Pro-tip or caption suggestion.

**Press release:** dateline, news lead, expanded context, multiple sourced quotes, photo caption, sponsor close.

**Admissions landing:** hero with trademark phrase. "Welcome [audience]" paragraph naming diversity stats. Persona navigation. Numbered application steps. Deadline countdown. Video showcase. CTA stack.

**Parent recruitment landing:** four-stat header bar (Total Enrollment, Faculty Ratio, Employment, Top Ranking). Welcome paragraph. Quoted parent testimonial. Sections for Differential Advantages, Admissions Requirements, Application Types, Long-Term Success. Apply Today / Email Admissions / Parent Portal CTAs.

**Value/tuition page:** aspirational headline. Value paragraph before any numbers. Outcomes stat. Ranking citation. Itemized cost block with aid package. Complimentary services table. Parent testimonials at bottom.

**Welcome Week materials:** cover with Welcome Home framing. Office letter. Day-by-day schedule with time blocks. Mandatory event markers. Sidebar callouts. City partnership feature. Resources directory.

**Qubein email:** short greeting, single-purpose body, warm sign-off, full signature block.

**Internal newsletter:** banner header. Events grid. Did You Know. Caring Campus Tip. News rundown. Student Highlight. Contact block.

**Athletics promo:** hero shot. Matchup, venue, time. Call to action. Sponsor or app download tag.

**Development letter:** salutation, three purposes named (advocacy, career networking, giving), specific fund named with figure, closer with title and email, 501(c)(3) disclaimer.

**Long-form magazine feature:** president's letter opening; pillar-based table of contents; definitional intros for each pillar; mix of long-form features, profiles, decade timelines, stat tables, and pull quotes; commemorative closing.

**Video transcript / chapter format:** numbered chapters (1. Introduction, 2. Why X Matters, 3. Real-World Opportunities); timestamps for each; description summary; related videos sidebar.

## What HPU does not sound like

Cynical. Ironic. Hedged. Apologetic. Dry-academic. Self-deprecating. Modest about cost or selectivity. If a sentence sounds like it could appear in any university's copy, rewrite it with a specific HPU name, number, or program.

## Honor Code and Fight Song handling

Both are HPU's property. Reference by name. Quote short, meaningful lines. Don't reproduce full text.

- Honor Code key line: "I will strive to be extraordinary in my academic studies and all other personal and professional pursuits."
- Fight Song key lines: "Choose to be Extraordinary®" rallying line; "Go HPU!" closer; Panther Shout "H-I-G-H P-O-I-N-T, High Point Panthers."

## Quick checklist before delivering

1. Right register for the content type (12 registers above; pick one and commit)
2. At least one named person, building, program, or stat in the piece
3. Reader addressed correctly (you for blog/admissions/student life; your student for parent; third person for press release/news; first person for Qubein; we for development)
4. A signature HPU phrase used where relevant (Qubein, Life Skills, Access to Innovators, You Were Meant to be Extraordinary®, Choose to be Extraordinary®, Welcome Home, the four pillars)
5. Trademark symbols preserved on ® terms
6. Rankings cited with consecutive-years language when used (e.g., "13 consecutive years")
7. Anchored to one of the four pillars when the piece is big enough to need a frame

## Gaps in the current corpus

The skill now covers blog (listicle, value-prop, feature, photo-op), press release (event, award, guest speaker), admissions landing, parent recruitment, application/deadlines, tuition/value, Welcome Week / Student Life, President Qubein first-person, internal/operational, athletics game-day, religious life, development/philanthropy, long-form magazine, and video/broadcast.

Still useful to add:
- Donor and major-gift solicitation (the formal "ask," not just the cultivation letter)
- Social captions specifically by platform (Instagram, X, TikTok)
- Athletics game recaps and post-game pressers
- Academic catalog and program-specific course descriptions
- Crisis communications or emergency messaging
- Faculty bio / faculty page voice
- Job listings and HR communications
- Trustee and Board communications

Send any of these and I'll add a section.